hints_latex:
Use the integral comparison test, i.e. find an integrand \emph{g(x)}
such that

\begin{align*}
\frac{e^{-x}}{2x-1} \leq g(x) \quad \text{and}\quad \int_1^\infty g(x)\,dx
\end{align*}
converges.

sols_latex:
On the interval $[1,\infty)$ we have that 2\emph{x}-1 $\geq$ 1 and so

\begin{align*}
\frac{e^{-x}}{2x-1} \leq e^{-x}
\end{align*} for all \emph{x} $\geq$ 1. Therefore

\begin{align*}
\int_1^\infty \frac{e^{-x}}{2x-1}\,dx \leq \int_1^\infty e^{-x}\,dx
\end{align*}

by the integral comparison test. Since the latter integral

\begin{align*}
\int_1^\infty e^{-x}\,dx
\end{align*} converges (see lecture notes or direct
calculation), the former integral also converges, by the integral
comparison test.
